nodes.body:
Thanks @kbuzzard and @101damnations for your suggestions!

In order to be more consistent with group cohomology, I have renamed the definitions. They are now `ZeroCochain`, etc. The difference is that I define a type `OneCycle`, where as in group cohomology there is a term `oneCocycles` in a `Submodule` type.
Can we add a reference to the literature for 1-cochains and 1-cocycles? I was just checking this over and realised that I didn't know one.
I have added a reference to http://www.numdam.org/item/10.24033/bsmf.1485.pdf (this is in French though!).

:v: joelriou can now approve this pull request. To approve and merge a pull request, simply reply with `bors r+`. More detailed instructions are available [here](https://bors.tech/documentation/getting-started/#reviewing-pull-requests).

Thanks!

Thanks for the reference; it doesn't do things in this generality but I've seen enough of this sort of thing now to know that it might be hard to find a reference which does! I left some more superficial comments but you've convinced me that mathematically these are the right definitions.

Thanks for the reference; it doesn't do things in this generality but I've seen enough of this sort of thing now to know that it might be hard to find a reference which does! I left some more superficial comments but you've convinced me that mathematically these are the right definitions.

bors d+

```suggestion
/-- A zero cochain consists of a family of sections. -/
```
I think maybe "satisfies the cocycle condition" or "satisfies a certain cocycle condition" is better -- right now the docstring can be misinterpreted as meaning "it satisfies any kind of condition".

Maybe it is worth adding some comment of the form "because we do not assume that the values of G are abelian, there is no general cohomology theory H^n, which is why we are only making definitions in low degree in this file".

Not really a concrete suggestion, but currently this file differs a little from the naming conventions in `Mathlib.RepresentationTheory.GroupCohomology.LowDegree`, where e.g. 1-cocycles are called `oneCocycles`. Maybe we should find some way to stay consistent. I'd be fine with changing my naming conventions if that helps; the subscripts you use look nice.

**[lint-bib]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion @Article{ frenkel1957, ```

**[lint-bib]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion url = {http://www.numdam.org/item?id=BSMF_1957__85__135_0} ```

**[lint-bib]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion @Article{ frenkel1957, ```

```suggestion
instance : Group (ZeroCochain G U) := Pi.group
```
I don't really know how much difference this makes. If you look at the term you generate with your proof (by naming it and then using `#print`), there's a random `id` in there presumably because you entered tactic mode or something. With my proof there's no `id` but on the other hand I don't know if this matters

```suggestion
  one := { ev := fun _ _ _ _ _ ↦ 1 }
```
I thought mathlib preferred `mapsto`. Do you not like it? I don't really know the style here, maybe both are fine?

```suggestion
    (γ⁻¹).ev i j a b = (γ.ev i j a b)⁻¹ := rfl
```
Again I don't know the canonical style but I don't put these spaces in myself. If you want to leave them, and you know this is OK style, that's fine.

```suggestion
    γ.ev i j a b = (γ.ev j i b a)⁻¹ := by
```
Again, if a space is OK and you want it, that's fine by me.

```suggestion
lemma refl (γ : OneCochain G U) : OneCohomologyRelation γ γ 1 := fun _ _ _ _ _ ↦ by simp
```
and similarly symm, trans (if `=>` is not mathlib style...)
